as explain:
> I've performed some debugging and found out that the problem was caused by the following code: `<div [innerHTML]="sanitizedContent"></div>`. What happens is that Angular hydration finds and hydrates the `<div>`, but after that the `innerHTML` binding just overrides everything inside that `<div>`, removing the content that was server-side rendered.
> 

I decided to write a full explain about hydration and how it work with dynamic HTML render content. It include 2 new titles:
- Angular APIs for DOM manipulation and dynamic content 
- Flick on hydration

I think this will be useful and help save about few weeks of developer working on that feature.

example code on branch application: https://github.com/hiepxanh/angular-hydration-flick

codesandbox link (I think have to create account): https://codesandbox.io/p/github/hiepxanh/angular-hydration-flick/application 

code example run result: 

``` typescript

@Component({
  standalone: true,
  selector: 'app-footer',
  template: `
  Footer should not empty <p [innerHTML]="content"> footer here </p>
  `,
  styles: [`
    :host { display: block; }
  `]
})
export class FooterComponent {
  platformId = inject(PLATFORM_ID);
  isServer = isPlatformServer(this.platformId);
  elementRef = inject(ElementRef);
  @HostBinding('attr.id') id!: string;
  content!: string;
  ngOnInit() {
    if (this.isServer) {
      // not work: the p tag will not update innerHTML
      this.content = 'footer content changed';
      // not work: the footer will not have id attribute
      this.id = 'id: server';
      // work: title display if you hover on footer content
      this.elementRef.nativeElement.setAttribute("title", `platform: ${this.platformId}`);
    }
  }
}
```

